{
  "card_id": "momentum",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Momentum",
  "aliases": [],
  "school": "Indicator Based",
  "definition": "Momentum is the speed and strength of price movement, indicating the velocity of change. High momentum features rapid, large directional candles; low momentum shows slow, indecisive action. Extreme momentum, such as when RSI breaks outside its Bollinger Bands, signals exceptionally strong movement that can lead to increased volatility and large subsequent price moves.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Evaluate the size and speed of candlesticks: large, consecutive candles in one direction indicate strong momentum.",
    "Use momentum oscillators (e.g., RSI, MACD, Stochastic RSI) to quantify momentum; extreme readings suggest strong directional momentum.",
    "Momentum shifts are indicated when the rate of price change alters, visible through oscillator crossovers or divergence from price.",
    "RSI line breaks above the upper Bollinger Band or below the lower Bollinger Band.",
    "The price preceding the break often exhibits low volatility or consolidation, causing the bands to tighten before the extreme momentum move."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Momentum gauges trend strength and reversal potential. High momentum confirms trend direction; slowing momentum suggests a possible reversal. Extreme momentum, like RSI breaking Bollinger Bands, marks a temporary extreme with uncertain direction, best avoided by beginners. Advanced traders may use it to seek reversal signals with price action at support/resistance, aiming for large moves as volatility expands. Momentum indicators help time entries/exits and identify divergences.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Failing to combine momentum signals with other technical variables, such as price action or support/resistance.",
    "Assuming extreme momentum will continue in the same direction without considering potential reversals.",
    "Trading solely based on RSI breaking Bollinger Bands without confirming entry with price action."
  ],
